Been waiting to do this session since I started newborn photography. By the grace of Allah, my family has been blessed with baby Hana. For indeed, with hardship comes ease. (Quran 94:5) This promise of Allah should help us be patient in times of hardship. We should know that whatever calamity strikes us will be eased and not continue forever. Hana is my late father’s dua come true. Ten months ago while in hospice he would make dua that my sister gets blessed with a child one day. As for me, he would make the same dua and make extra dua that I’d succeed in newborn photography. He always supported all our dreams and passions. This newborn session for Hana was a full circle moment for all his answered duas. 

My sister and brother-in-law named her Hana, which means happiness, joy, and felicity. Happiness is what we all felt in my father’s presence. Joy is something he always effortlessly brought to any room. Felicity was simply seen in his vibrant smile.

As I was looking for a photo of my father for this frame idea I had, I came across the next two photos from both mine and my sister’s wedding day. These photos serve as a reminder to me of how lucky I was to have experienced a father’s unconditional love. I can only imagine how much of an amazing Nana he would be. Saying goodbye to a loved one while simultaneously experiencing the joy of welcoming another into this world is one of Allah’s greatest blessings🤍 Please keep my late father, sister, and my new bestie Hana in your duas.

In this digital age we take loads of photos with our phones. But when it comes to creating something tangible on our walls or albums, mobile photos are not that great for printing and enlarging. I may have many wishes but one matters the most: To be reunited in Jannah with everyone I love. Ya Allah, may You grant each one of us the highest ranks of paradise and may You make our reunion spectacular. 

It’s been 365 days since my my father has left this world. Today serves as another painful reminder that the amazing man who raised me isn't with us anymore. He has left me with countless blessings and his love, compassion, and duas. He always had the biggest smile despite how much he suffered in his lifetime. The smile planted on his beautiful face during his funeral is what brings peace during days I am a wreck. May Allah forgive him and grant him the highest place in Jannah and grant me the strength and patience to go on to live the life he wanted for me. 

“May God accept this struggle as beautiful patience. So here's to learning to live with a bigger hole in my heart and finding ways to expand what's left; to having the most beautiful opinion of my Lord; to allowing this pain to make me more strong and tender.” -@ahlamsaid

Motherhood photography sessions are now my favorite milestone to photograph. They are a celebration of your role as a mother, the tender love you have for your children and the authentic connections you share with them. Thank you @saika.says for letting me always test my new photography ventures on you and baby Eli🥹

Last week I attended a masterclass with one of the best in maternity photography, @lolamelani. She started doing photoshoots in her apartment in Brooklyn and is now is mentoring photographers like me all over the world. She caters to the needs of all her students. I mentioned to her how I often struggle with studio maternity sessions because majority of my clients are conservative and they wouldn’t do the typical nude photos or the huge ruffle maternity gowns that they usually have to settle for in other studios. So I wanted to offer something in between and still make them feel beautiful during this milestone while having them remain true to their values. She gave me the idea of building a high quality modest wardrobe catered to my clientele and taught me tips and tricks on how to make any fabric appear to be modest just like in the photo above. Over the last week I have created a beautiful collection of modest outfits for my clients and can’t wait to implement all the technical lighting tricks Lola has taught me to capture the most timeless photos. Forever grateful for her and all my amazing mentors who are so generous with taking the time to teach their craft. Can I coin the term “modest maternity session” now?🤌🏼
Love grows here🌸

A sitter session, as the name suggests, is a photoshoot for babies who can confidently sit up unsupported. Typically this is from about 7-8 months of age. What makes these sessions such a treat is that babies around this stage are becoming very smiley, playful and curious! So we usually get great big smiles and fun expressions.
Capturing all the newborn sweetness one pose at a time. Love me a wide-eyed baby. Gianna, 13 days old.

Me to ChatGPT: Is newborn photography worth investing in?

ChatGPT: While newborn photography session fees and collections may seem expensive, they are an investment that will increase in value as the years go by. As your child grows into a toddler and a teenager and even an adult, you will have their newborn images—and hopefully other photos as well—to look back on to remind you where this unique and special journey began. That’s something you simply cannot put a price on.

The one detail about our weddings non of us can/could ever fathom is/was the absence of our mothers. 

Tasfia lost her mother to cancer when she was only eight.

20 years later, Tasfia married her forever, a seat reserved, front row, in honor of her late mother. 

And on this day, her sister surprised her with a canvas of their late mother and dadi, standing side by side next to Tasfia & her husband, in what she imagined they would wear on this joyous occasion. 

-

Tasfia may not be the first bride to get married without her mother by her side. But when you’re going through the journey, feeling all the emotions, walking down the aisle, with your loved friends and family surrounding you, I imagine, it feels like you are. 

May Allah grant her mother & dadi the highest ranks of Jannah and allow them all to reunite one day. And until then, Tasfia, may He continue filling your days with an abundance of laughter and joy. insha’Allah.

Tasfia and Shafkat’s Nikkah took place in their beautiful backyard. From making an entrance with most powerful verse of the Qur'an that Allah (SWT) has revealed to seek protection, guidance, sustenance, and blessings to honoring the memory of a loved one who has passed away. These beautiful and sentimental details are a constant reminder of why we do what we do as photographers. To evoke emotion in photography simply means your photos say something. They tell a story—rather than merely creating a record of a place or moment—moving your audience in a myriad of ways ranging from happiness, sadness, sorrow, despair, thoughtfulness, love, and so on🤍
